circRNAs

14/12/2020

Donnes :

Les trois fichiers de comptage :

  • total RNAseq : sus_scrofa_linear_counts.tsv
  • mRNAseq : raffine.gnexpr.readcount.matrix.tsv
  • circRNA : sus_scrofa_bsj_gene_counts.tsv => utilis simplement pour identifier les gnes produisant des circRNAs

3 chantillons :

  • ssc_testis_1 (FR22JFZ201100831) : animal 31
  • ssc_testis_2 (FR62ND6201203305) : animal 05
  • ssc_testis_3 (FR79JCW201106154) : animal 54

Consignes :

  • extraire les comptages pour les chantillons mentionns
  • normaliser les donnes (paragraphe normalisation : http://genoweb.toulouse.inra.fr/~faraut/circRNAFrontiers)
  • faire un plot et une rgression linaire pour chaque animal (nuage de points) : comparer lexpression estime avec du totalRNAseq celle estime avec du mRNAseq => Raliser une rgression linaire entre ces estimations (1 par animal)
  • faire apparatre dans le plot les gnes qui produisent des ARNcirc (fichier sus_scrofa_bsj_gene_counts.tsv)
  • montrer que la relation linaire nest pas la mme pour ces derniers

df_linear = read.table("sus_scrofa_linear_counts.tsv", sep="\t", header=TRUE)
df_circrna = read.table("sus_scrofa_bsj_gene_counts.tsv", sep="\t", header=TRUE)
df_readcount = read.table("raffine.gnexpr.readcount.matrix.tsv", sep="\t", header=TRUE)
df_readcount = cbind(gene_id = rownames(df_readcount), df_readcount, row.names = NULL)

df_fr_sc = read.table("junc_ratio/circexplorer/sus_scrofa_junc_ratio_counts.tsv", sep="\t", header=TRUE)
df_fr_sc = ddply(df_fr_sc,"gene_id",numcolwise(sum))

commom_gene_ids = intersect(df_linear$gene_id, df_readcount$gene_id)

# Count per million reads : 

df_linear[,-1] = apply(df_linear[,-1] ,2,function(x){(x/sum(x))*1000000})
df_circrna[,-1] = apply(df_circrna[,-1],2,function(x){(x/sum(x))*1000000})

2. Normalisation des donnes :

# Create a function to normalize data:
normalization <- function(dataframe) {
  Counts = round(data.frame(dataframe[,-1], row.names = dataframe[,1]))
  pseudoCounts <- log2(Counts+1)
  dgeCounts <- DGEList(Counts)

  # We normalize the data in order to take into account the different overall number of reads between samples
  dgeCounts <- calcNormFactors(dgeCounts, method="TMM")
  eff.lib.size <- dgeCounts$samples$lib.size*dgeCounts$samples$norm.factors
  normCounts <- sweep(dgeCounts$counts, 2, eff.lib.size, "/")*10^6
  
  # which is equivalent to normCounts <- cpm(dgeFull)
  pseudoNormCounts <- log2(normCounts + 1)
  df_norm = data.frame(pseudoNormCounts)
  df_norm = cbind(gene_id = rownames(df_norm), df_norm, row.names = NULL)
  return(df_norm)
}

# Apply the normalize function on data:
df_linear_norm = normalization(dataframe = df_linear)
df_circrna_norm = normalization(dataframe = df_circrna)
df_readc_norm = normalization(dataframe = df_readcount)

# Delete fr values if NA for circ :

4. Rgression linaire (nuage de points) :

ggp <- function(dataframe, title) {
  
  circpal <- colorRampPalette(c("saddlebrown", "white"))
  #circpal(10)
  #nocircpal <- colorRampPalette(c("", ""))
  
  dataframe$col = as.factor(as.vector(unlist(lapply(dataframe$circ, function(x){if(is.na(x)){"no circ"} else{"circ"}}))))

  ggplot(dataframe, aes(x=as.numeric(linear), y=as.numeric(readc))) +
 
  geom_point(aes(x=as.numeric(linear), y=as.numeric(readc), color = col)) +
  geom_smooth(method=lm, se=FALSE, fullrange=TRUE, aes(x=as.numeric(linear), y=as.numeric(readc)), colour="dodgerblue2") +
  geom_point(data = subset(dataframe, col == 'circ'), aes(x=as.numeric(linear), y=as.numeric(readc), color = col)) +
  geom_smooth(method=lm, se=FALSE, fullrange=TRUE, data = subset(dataframe, col == 'circ'), aes(x=as.numeric(linear), y=as.numeric(readc)), colour="saddlebrown") +
  labs(title=title, x = "TotalRNAseq expression level (read count/gene norm)",
                    y = "mRNAseq expression level (read count/gene norm)") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5), legend.position="bottom") +
  
  scale_color_manual(values=c('saddlebrown', 'dodgerblue2'), 
                     name="Genes",
                     labels=c("Involved in the production of circRNA", 
                     "Not involved in the production of circRNA")) +
  
  stat_fit_glance(data = subset(dataframe, col == 'no circ'), colour="dodgerblue2",
                  method = "lm", label.x = "left", label.y = 1, size=3.5,
                  method.args = list(formula = y ~ x),
                  mapping = aes(label = sprintf('r^2~"="~%.3f', stat(r.squared))), parse = TRUE) +
  stat_fit_glance(data = subset(dataframe, col == 'circ'), colour="saddlebrown",
                  method = "lm", label.x = "left", label.y = "top", size=3.5,
                  method.args = list(formula = y ~ x),
                  mapping = aes(label = sprintf('r^2~"="~%.3f', stat(r.squared))), parse = TRUE)
}

ggp_1 = ggp(dataframe = df_ssc_1, "ssc_testis_1 (31)")
ggp_2 = ggp(dataframe = df_ssc_2, "ssc_testis_2 (05)")
ggp_3 = ggp(dataframe = df_ssc_3, "ssc_testis_3 (54)")

suppressWarnings(suppressMessages(grid.arrange(ggp_1, ggp_2, ggp_3, ncol = 2, nrow = 2)))

Conclusion :

ggp <- function(dataframe, title) {
  
  dataframe$col = as.factor(as.vector(unlist(lapply(dataframe$circ, function(x){if(is.na(x)){"no circ"} else{"circ"}}))))
  
  ggplot(dataframe) +
    
    labs(title=title, x = "TotalRNAseq expression level (read count/gene norm)",
                      y = "mRNAseq expression level (read count/gene norm)") +
    theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5), legend.position="bottom") +
    
    geom_point(aes(x=linear, y=readc, color = fr)) +
    geom_smooth(method=lm, se=FALSE, fullrange=TRUE, aes(x=linear, y=readc), colour="grey50") +
    
    geom_point(data = subset(dataframe, is.na(fr) == F), aes(x=linear, y=readc, color = fr)) +
    geom_smooth(method=lm, se=FALSE, fullrange=TRUE, data = subset(dataframe, col == 'circ'), aes(x=linear, y=readc), colour="saddlebrown") +
  
    scale_color_manual(values=c('grey50', 'dodgerblue2'), name="Genes",
                       labels=c("Involved in the production of circRNA", "Not involved in the production of circRNA")) +
    
    scale_color_gradient(low="saddlebrown", high="red") 
}

ggp_1 = ggp(dataframe = df_ssc_1, "ssc_testis_1 (31)")
